~~~
{: #api-request title="Example REST Registration API with COSE (request)"}

#### Signature

The signatures payload is a CBOR/JSON Claims Set that MUST include the Claim Key for the `hri` with the value containing the {{req-model}} model. Claim Keys of `nbf`, `iat`, and `exp` are RECOMMENDED. The `aud` Claim Key can is OPTIONAL and used to signal the exact HHIT Issuing entity to process the OME Token contents when it contains the value of the HHIT as an IPv6 address string as defined in {{RFC4291, Section 2.2}}.

##### Self-Signed

When a key is encapsulated in the OME Token's inner payload the public key to verify the signature MUST be included in the protected header in the `jwk` for JOSE or `kccs` for COSE parameter. This same logic applies when a multi-signature object is used in either COSE/JOSE. This case only applies when a *Registrant* has no prior relationship with the OME and is starting from nothing.

##### Proxy-Signed

If the key used to sign the COSE/JOSE object is already registered and has an HHIT then the unprotected header MUST contain the `kid` parameter with the HHIT. See {{ip6-handling}} for encoding of the `kid`. A multi-signature object has the `kid` as defined here in its each unique signature objects header.

#### Encryption

An OME Token from a *Registrant* MUST be encrypted as it may contain Personally Identifiable Information (PII). The encryption algorithm selection and policies are left for OME policy and MUST be provided to *Registrant*s. It is strongly RECOMMENDED that asymmetric keys are used for encryption. The encryption payload is the COSE/JOSE signature object of {{signature}}. *Registrants* SHOULD set the `content type` parameter in the header of the encryption object to signal the content type of the encrypted payload.

Encryption is done with Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman (ECDH) using Ephemeral-Static (ES) keying. The static key is provided by the OME while the a unique ephemeral key is provided by the *Registrant* for each OME Token and/or recipient. The OME MUST provide static keys through public methods such as the DNS or an HTTPS GET endpoint. Refer to relevant COSE or JOSE specifications for using ECDH with COSE/JOSE encryption objects.

## OME Processing & Response

### Request Validation & Processing {#req-valid}

All requests MUST pass the following checks before following {{req-approve}}:

1. The OME Token signature validates with an acceptable public key
2. The CSR signature passes with embedded public key
3. The public key in CSR is unique to the OME's scope
4. OME constructs using their HID and the CSR's public key an HHIT and;
    * If an HHIT is provided by *Registrant* in CSR ensure they are equivalent
    * Confirm the HHIT is unique in the OME's authority of the hierarchy
5. Additional data, if any, in the OME Token is acceptable; see {{oaas}}

If any of the above checks fail, the OME follows {{req-deny}}.

#### Inquiry Approval {#req-approve}

Once processed as a "pass" the OME MUST generate at least OKIX-compliant certificates and based on the use case MAY generate other artifacts. The OME MUST store these certificates and other artifacts in their *Registry* and also update the relative *Authoritative Name Server* accordingly.

The response models `entity-id`'s and `key-id`'s MUST match those provided by the *Registrant*.

#### Inquiry Rejection {#req-deny}

A section of the response model ({{model-resp}}) is set aside to carry errors and is OPTIONAL. A non-exhaustive list of examples of rejection reasons are:

- OME Token not encrypted
- Public key not found/provided
- Invalid/missing model element(s)
- Non-conformance with OME policy/policies

### Response Model {#resp-model}

~~~ ascii-text
{::include cddl/response.cddl}
~~~
{: #model-resp title="Response Model CDDL"}

*success*:
: A map of the entities successfully registered from an inquiry.

*entity-id*:
: A string or integer key, as part of the *success* map, provided by the *Registrant* in the inquiry.

*keys*:
: A map of the keys successfully registered for an entity from an inquiry. Each elements value is a map containing artifacts of the registration associated with the specific key and MUST have an element containing the canonical registration certificate.

*key-id*:
: A string or integer key, as part of the *keys* map for each *entity*, set by the *Registrant* in the inquiry.

*failure*:
: List of registration failures, each denoting the entity and/or key by their respective IDs. When `eid` or `kid` is `null` it implies that all of that type are denoting the same failure.

### Response OME Token {#resp-wt}

The OME Response Token follows the same encoding as {{req-wt}} but instead of using a Claim Key of `hri` it is `hrr` and is signed by the OME following {{proxy-signed}}. The OME Token MAY be encrypted using the same shared secret generated during {{encryption}}. {{api-response}} shows a typical OME Token being returned to a *Registrant*.

